2A>(5/21/02 1:51:24 pm)</font><br>   <a href=http://pub94.ezboard.com/ffirionaviefrm1.showAddReplyScreenFromWeb?topicID=1984.topic&index=47>Reply</a>   </td><td valign=top align=left class=m><span class=title> Re: Brad and EQ</span><hr size=1> I think there has always been 3 main problems with dungeons<br>
------------------------<br>
<br>
You missed the big one: TIME.<br>
<br>
Dungeon crawls take a big time investment. Screaming for a group in [insert Kunark zone appropriate for your level] can be done in an hour or two.<br>
<br>
I always figured I needed a 4-5 hour commitment minimum to a good dungeon crawl (Befallen, Guks, Najena, TOFS, CC, etc.)<br>
<br>
In all the games I've played, the most fun evening I ever had was a long crawl with 4 friends through Droga/Nurga. Nobody had ever been there. Most stuff was blue, but in enough numbers and with freinds enough to scare us. It was incredible. But we started at 7pm and ended around 2am--7 hours. Work nights I have to be in bed by 10pm or I'm overtired and rip (L)users heads off when they bother me.  <br>
<br>
Kunark outdoor zones offered EQ to the casual gamer. Even with them, the time factor required of EQ was one of many reasons that I left the game. The game was my friends and I just didn't have the time to catch up with them in levels.<br>
<br>
On the subject in general of the latter stages of games, you might look at Designer Dragon's site about the evolution of online games (<!--EZCODE AUTOLINK START--><a href="http://www.legendmud.org/raph/).">www.legendmud.org/raph/).</a><!--EZCODE AUTOLINK END--> He was the lead designer of UO for a long period--the Brad of that game. One of the things he notes is that as time goes on, the low and mid-game move higher and higher. Creatures are more easily taken out because strategies have been worked out. The game (whatever game) has a sort of inflation towards the high end. Some of the simplification of the under 10 game seems to mirror this thought. <br>
