<A HREF="http://www.magelo.com/eq_view_profile.html?num=220056">Wraithbane's Magelo Profile</A> </p><i></i></td></tr><tr bgcolor=d1c3b5><td nowrap width=20% valign=top align=left><span class=title> <A HREF=http://pub94.ezboard.com/ukrazakthule.showPublicProfile?language=EN>Krazak Thule</A></span><br> <span class=usertitle>Registered User</span><br>  Posts: 43<br> <font color=#A62A2A>(5/21/02 3:17:55 pm)</font><br>   <a href=http://pub94.ezboard.com/ffirionaviefrm1.showAddReplyScreenFromWeb?topicID=1984.topic&index=49>Reply</a>   </td><td valign=top align=left class=m><span class=title> Dungeons</span><hr size=1> <!--EZCODE QUOTE START--><blockquote><b><i>Quote:</i></b><hr> <br>
I always figured I needed a 4-5 hour commitment minimum to a good dungeon crawl (Befallen, Guks, Najena, TOFS, CC, etc.)<br>
<hr></blockquote><!--EZCODE QUOTE END--><br>
<br>
I mean no offense here, so don't take this the wrong way, but clearly I would say you are someone who has never stepped foot into a dungeon then, because your time assessment (for the most part) is all wrong. <br>
<br>
When Cazic Thule was a popular zone (pre-kunark), you could walk into that zone and have a group in 5 minutes. It was fairly small dungeon, with a lot of isolated side-rooms (which helped reduce zone-wide trains), that only would take a few seconds to get to. There were plenty of times I would logon, and within 2-5 minutes I was physically in a group and fighting. <br>
<br>
Now, mind you, it wasn't this way when I first stepped foot in that zone. At lower levels, my first few trips there, nobody knew me, and it took time to build a reputation. But in a dungeon like that, in a few days time, you can build a reputation, and then finding a group fast is no problem. <br>
<br>
(sidebar: Cazic Thule, and Guk, are two of the best designed multiplayer dungeons I've seen. I only wish Verant had made more dungeons like them. Unrest, Karnors, and Mistmoore suffered from the one-main-path problem, which would cause any train to cover the whole zone... and then the Kunark dungeons really ruined it, because they were almost all designed in a linear fashion, and not to be &quot;camped&quot;)<br>
<br>
I've played it both ways. I've spent time in nearly every dungeon that was popular, and I've put 3-4 twinks through the Kunark outdoor zones as well. For most any situation, finding a group comes down to reputation. It can actually be faster to find a group in a dungeon, depending on the popularity of the zone and the reputation you have earned. <br>
<br>
Most of the dungeons I prefer are not dungeons that are linear. I think the linear dungeons, while good for single player games, basically suck for games like EQ. People need to be able to treat a dungeon the same way they treat an outdoor zone: login, shout for group, find one, get there, and begin fighting in a designated &quot;camp&quot;. Moving around in a linear dungeon, like Howling Stones, or Nurga, is fine, *if* you have the time committment.  <br>
<br>
Dungeons like Nurga and Droga, I have railed against since thier inception. They are totally stupid designs. <br>
<br>
But dungeons like Cazic Thule, Guk, and portions of Velks, are designed very well. You can get in there, group up, and fight, in the same amount of time that it would take you to do so in an outdoor zone. <br>
<br>
The problem with Kunark released dungeons, being linear, is that they changed the perception for gamers. People who had never stepped foot into Unrest, Guk or Cazic Thule had no idea what a well designed multi-player dungeon was like. They only saw dungeons like Droga and Nurga, and ran screaming. <!--EZCODE BOLD START--><b> Because you are right about those dungeons</b><!--EZCODE BOLD END-->: They are linear, and they require a serious time committment if you want to &quot;crawl&quot; through them. <br>
<br>
The point is, not every dungeon was designed that way, and many of the old-world dungeons make far better exp zones than anyth outdoor zone anywhere else on Norrath. But, unless it's a high level dungeon, it can be useless to a lower level group, who doesn't possess the high-level tools to do dungeons well. <br>
<br>
For most people, their first exposure to a &quot;dungeon&quot;, post-Kunark, was Karnor's Castle. That's a level 50 dungeon. At that time, druids have egress and evac and clerics finally have a decent rez. That dungeon becomes doable. <br>
<br>
But pre-level 50, dungeons aren't worth the hassle. They were before Kunark was released, because until Kunark came out, nothing compared to the dungeons. Post Kunark, it was simple: Why go to Cazic Thule when you could get the SAME experience modifier in an outdoor, safe, Kunark zone? <br>
<br>
People chose outdoors. And rightfully so. Without a good cleric rez, and evacs, and corpse summons, why go to all the bother? Pre-Kunark you were almost forced to, and we all made it work. But give the players an easy alternative, and what are they going to chose? <br>
<br>
<br>
I've met a lot of total n00bs to EQ in the past year, on my old server, while playing twinks. Most of them had no idea what the old-school dungeons were like. They had no idea how good the exp and loot were. If you *could* manage to get some of those people to go with you, they almost always loved it. But it was so hard to get them to go. Most people hated that the dungeons were so far away from bind points for melee, and that rezzes and such were far and few between. <br>
<br>
I think if you gave clerics the proper rezzes at low levels, and druid/wizards the proper evacs/egress/ports at lower levels, then certain dungeons might rise in popularity. <br>
<br>
At any rate.. I feel mostly that it's a design flaw. I can't fault players for being afraid, or having a misconception about the time committment. Nobody wants to lose their corpse, and nobody wants to spend more than few minutes on CR. I wish things were different, but they're not. <br>
<br>
<br>
<br>
<br>
<br>
<br>
<br>
<br>
